{
  "texts": [
    "Approaches that \"chunk\" documents into smaller segments and compute similarities between corresponding segments can alleviate some of these distortions, but they add complexity to the analysis and require a clear understanding of the conceptual role of these different chunks.",
    "In economic applications, this distinction between partial and near-complete overlap may lie at the heart of whether two technologies are complements or substitutes, yet a single similarity value may obscure such nuances.",
    "Note that this challenge is essentially a technical one, likely to be solved at least in the medium run.",
    "Another practical consideration is the distribution of similarity scores that different methods produce.",
    "Traditional approaches like TF-IDF and Bag-of-Words yield sparse and highly skewed similarity distributions, whereas LLM-based embeddings often generate smoother distributions."
  ]
}